The 2016 [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom) [European Union](/European_Union) membership referendum, often prosaically referred to as the EU referendum or, more dramatically, the [Brexit](/Brexit) referendum, was a political spectacle staged on 23 June 2016. Across the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom) and its distant outpost, [Gibraltar](/Gibraltar), the populace was asked to ponder a question that, in hindsight, seems almost quaint in its simplicity: should the country remain nestled within the [European Union](/European_Union) or embark on a journey outside its familiar embrace? This momentous decision was facilitated by the rather dryly titled [European Union Referendum Act 2015](/European_Union_Referendum_Act_2015). The outcome, a vote in favour of departure, predictably triggered a cascade of political maneuvering and the eventual, convoluted process of the country's [withdrawal from the EU](/Withdrawal_from_the_EU), which, for better or worse, became universally known as "[Brexit](/Brexit)".

For decades, [since 1973](/Accession_of_the_United_Kingdom_to_the_European_Communities) to be precise, the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom) had been entrenched as a [member state of the EU](/Member_state_of_the_EU), or its predecessor, the [European Communities](/European_Communities) – chiefly the [European Economic Community](/European_Economic_Community) – alongside a host of other international affiliations. This long-standing relationship, however, was never entirely without its domestic squabbles, particularly regarding the rather abstract, yet deeply felt, concept of national sovereignty. An earlier attempt to quell these perennial debates, [a referendum on continued membership of the European Communities](/1975_United_Kingdom_European_Communities_membership_referendum), was held in 1975. A reassuring 67% of voters, on a turnout of 64.6%, opted to stay, seemingly settling the matter for a generation. &#91;1&#93; Yet, between 1975 and 2016, the quiet, persistent march of [European integration](/European_integration) continued. Subsequent EC/EU treaties and agreements, each deepening the ties, were ratified by the [UK Parliament](/UK_Parliament) without the inconvenience of public consultation. The stage was thus set for a fresh round of existential angst.

Following the [Conservative Party](/Conservative_Party_(UK))'s unexpected, yet decisive, victory in the [2015 general election](/2015_United_Kingdom_general_election), a key manifesto pledge was dusted off: a new referendum. This promise, once perhaps a strategic gambit, now became the legal cornerstone for the [European Union Referendum Act 2015](/European_Union_Referendum_Act_2015). In a parallel act of political theatre, then-Prime Minister [David Cameron](/David_Cameron) embarked on [a renegotiation of the terms of EU membership](/2015%E2%80%932016_United_Kingdom_renegotiation_of_European_Union_membership), presumably to sweeten the deal for a 'Remain' vote. It's crucial, if often overlooked, to note that this referendum, despite its monumental implications, was technically non-binding. The ancient, revered principle of [parliamentary sovereignty](/Parliamentary_sovereignty_in_the_United_Kingdom) meant Parliament could, in theory, ignore the result. However, the government, with a straight face, promised to implement the outcome, a promise that, like many in politics, would be tested by the harsh glare of reality. &#91;2&#93;

The official period for [campaigning](/Campaigning_in_the_2016_United_Kingdom_European_Union_membership_referendum) stretched from 15 April to 23 June 2016, a period that felt considerably longer to anyone unfortunate enough to be paying attention. On the side of continued membership, the officially designated champion was [Britain Stronger in Europe](/Britain_Stronger_in_Europe). Opposing them, advocating for departure, was [Vote Leave](/Vote_Leave). &#91;3&#93; Beyond these primary gladiators, a veritable menagerie of other groups, political parties, businesses, trade unions, newspapers, and prominent individuals joined the fray, demonstrating that conviction, or at least self-interest, knew no single political affiliation. The 'Remain' camp garnered support from the likes of [Labour](/Labour_Party_(UK)), the [Liberal Democrats](/Liberal_Democrats_(UK)), the [Scottish National Party](/Scottish_National_Party), [Plaid Cymru](/Plaid_Cymru), and the [Green Party](/Green_Party_of_England_and_Wales). &#91;4&#93; &#91;5&#93; &#91;6&#93; &#91;7&#93; Conversely, the [UK Independence Party](/UK_Independence_Party), true to its singular purpose, was a fervent proponent of leaving. &#91;8&#93; The [Conservative Party](/Conservative_Party_(UK)), in a feat of political acrobatics, declared itself officially neutral, &#91;9&#93; though it allowed its Members of Parliament, much like their Labour counterparts, the freedom to publicly campaign for either side. &#91;10&#93; &#91;11&#93; The [issues](/Issues_in_the_2016_United_Kingdom_European_Union_membership_referendum) dominating the discourse were, predictably, the economic implications of membership – the supposed costs and benefits – alongside the often-contentious matters of [freedom of movement](/Freedom_of_movement_for_workers_in_the_European_Union) and broader migration. As is often the case in such high-stakes contests, the campaign was not without its shadows, with several [allegations of unlawful campaigning](/Allegations_of_unlawful_campaigning_in_the_2016_EU_referendum) and even whispers of [Russian interference](/Russian_interference_in_the_2016_Brexit_referendum) surfacing both during and after the vote.

When [the results](/Results_of_the_2016_United_Kingdom_European_Union_membership_referendum) finally trickled in, the nation, and indeed the world, learned that 51.9% of votes cast were in favour of leaving. This aggregate figure, however, masked a stark geographical divide. Most areas across [England](/England) and [Wales](/Wales) delivered a majority for Leave, while voters in [Scotland](/Scotland), [Northern Ireland](/Northern_Ireland), the sprawling metropolis of [Greater London](/Greater_London), and the resilient enclave of Gibraltar predominantly chose Remain. Post-mortem analyses quickly established clear correlations between voter preference and factors such as age, educational attainment, and various socioeconomic markers. The ensuing examination of the [causes and reasoning](/Causes_of_the_vote_in_favour_of_Brexit) behind the Leave vote became a cottage industry of its own. [Immediately after the result](/Aftermath_of_the_2016_United_Kingdom_European_Union_membership_referendum), financial markets, ever so sensitive to uncertainty, registered their displeasure worldwide. [David Cameron](/David_Cameron), having set the ball rolling, promptly announced his resignation as prime minister and [leader of the Conservative Party](/Leader_of_the_Conservative_Party_(UK)), making good on his promise by July. The referendum's seismic shock reverberated globally, prompting [an array of international reactions](/International_reactions_to_the_2016_United_Kingdom_European_Union_membership_referendum). Domestically, even the opposition leader, [Jeremy Corbyn](/Jeremy_Corbyn), found his position precarious, facing [a Labour Party leadership challenge](/2016_Labour_Party_leadership_election_(UK)) in the wake of the political upheaval. Ultimately, in 2017, the [UK gave formal notice](/United_Kingdom_invocation_of_Article_50_of_the_Treaty_on_European_Union) of its intent to withdraw, a process that, after years of tortuous negotiations, was formalised in 2020.

