Further information: [Accession of the United Kingdom to the European Communities](/Accession_of_the_United_Kingdom_to_the_European_Communities), [European Communities Act 1972 (UK)](/European_Communities_Act_1972_(UK)), and [European Union Act 2011](/European_Union_Act_2011)

The genesis of the [European Communities](/European_Communities) can be traced back to the 1950s—a period of ambitious post-war reconstruction and integration. This era saw the establishment of the [European Coal and Steel Community](/European_Coal_and_Steel_Community) (ECSC) in 1952, followed by the [European Atomic Energy Community](/European_Atomic_Energy_Community) (EAEC or Euratom) and the [European Economic Community](/European_Economic_Community) (EEC) in 1957. &#91;12&#93; The EEC, often informally dubbed the "Common Market," represented the most expansive of these ventures, aiming for broad economic integration. The [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom), always one for a dramatic entrance, initially sought to join in 1961, only to be met with a decisive veto from France. &#91;12&#93; A subsequent application proved successful, and the UK finally became a member in 1973. Two years later, a [national referendum](/1975_United_Kingdom_European_Communities_membership_referendum) was held to gauge public sentiment on continued EC membership, with 67.2% of voters endorsing the status quo on a national turnout of 64.6%. &#91;12&#93;

However, this public approval was not sought again. Following the 1975 vote, no further referendums were deemed necessary on the evolving relationship between the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom) and the broader European project. Successive British governments, seemingly content with parliamentary oversight, continued to integrate the nation further into the European framework. This integration gained significant momentum when the [Maastricht Treaty](/Maastricht_Treaty) officially brought forth the [European Union](/European_Union) (EU) in 1993, which subsumed and, after the [Lisbon Treaty](/Lisbon_Treaty), effectively succeeded the original European Communities. &#91;12&#93; &#91;13&#93; This steady, unconsulted deepening of ties would, of course, become a focal point for future discontent.

Growing pressure for a referendum

See also: [Bloomberg speech](/Bloomberg_speech), [2014 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom](/2014_European_Parliament_election_in_the_United_Kingdom), and [2015 United Kingdom general election](/2015_United_Kingdom_general_election)

The seeds of the 2016 referendum were sown well before its official announcement. At the May [2012 NATO summit meeting](/2012_Chicago_summit), a notable conversation reportedly occurred involving then-UK Prime Minister [David Cameron](/David_Cameron), [Foreign Secretary](/Foreign_Secretary_(United_Kingdom)) [William Hague](/William_Hague), and [Ed Llewellyn](/Edward_Llewellyn,_Baron_Llewellyn_of_Steep). The topic? The rather pragmatic idea of leveraging a [European Union](/European_Union) referendum as a strategic concession to appease the increasingly vocal [Eurosceptic](/Eurosceptic) faction within the [Conservative Party](/Conservative_Party_(UK)). &#91;14&#93; This internal party management strategy would, ironically, spiral into a national, then international, phenomenon.

Just a month later, on 20 June 2012, a [private member's](/Private_member%27s_bill) [bill](/European_Communities_Act_1972_(Repeal)_Bills) comprising three clauses was introduced into the venerable [House of Commons](/House_of_Commons_of_the_United_Kingdom). Its sponsor was the then-Eurosceptic [MP](/Member_of_parliament) [Douglas Carswell](/Douglas_Carswell), and its intent was clear: to terminate the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom)'s [EU](/European_Union) membership and repeal the foundational [European Communities Act 1972](/European_Communities_Act_1972_(UK)). Notably, this bill, while radical in its aim, contained no explicit commitment to holding a referendum. It managed to secure a second reading, enduring a brisk half-hour debate in the chamber on 26 October 2012, but ultimately failed to progress further, a mere precursor to the legislative battles to come. &#91;15&#93;

Undeterred by previous legislative hurdles, Conservative [MP](/Member_of_parliament) James Wharton took up the mantle in 2013, introducing his own [Private member's](/Private_member%27s_bill) [bill](/European_Union_(Referendum)_Bill_2013%E2%80%9314) to the [House of Commons](/House_of_Commons_of_the_United_Kingdom). This legislation was more direct, explicitly committing the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom) to holding a referendum on its continued [EU](/European_Union) membership by the close of 2017. It successfully navigated all its stages in the lower chamber, only to be unceremoniously blocked in the [House of Lords](/House_of_Lords) in early 2014. The political will for a referendum was clearly building, but the legislative path remained fraught.

During the run-up to the [2015 general election](/2015_United_Kingdom_general_election) campaign, [David Cameron](/David_Cameron), ever the pragmatist, made a defining promise: if the [Conservative Party](/Conservative_Party_(UK)) secured a majority government, he would first renegotiate the terms of the [UK](/United_Kingdom)'s [EU](/European_Union) membership, and then, crucially, hold a referendum on the subject. This pledge, perhaps intended to unite his party, would ultimately reshape the nation.

In January 2013, prior to the election, Cameron delivered his much-anticipated [Bloomberg speech](/Bloomberg_speech). In it, he reiterated his commitment: should the Conservatives achieve a parliamentary majority in the [2015 general election](/2015_United_Kingdom_general_election), the [British government](/British_government) would undertake negotiations to secure what he termed "more favourable arrangements" for the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom)'s ongoing [EU](/European_Union) membership. Only after this, he promised, would a referendum be held, offering the stark choice of remaining in or leaving the [European Union](/European_Union) (under either the existing or newly negotiated terms). &#91;16&#93; To demonstrate their resolve, the [Conservative Party](/Conservative_Party_(UK)) published a draft [EU Referendum Bill](/European_Union_(Referendum)_Bill_2013%E2%80%9314) in May 2013, laying out their roadmap for renegotiation followed by the "in-out" vote. &#91;17&#93; This draft legislation stipulated that the referendum had to be conducted no later than 31 December 2017. &#91;18&#93;

The draft legislation then found its champion in Conservative [MP](/Member_of_parliament) [James Wharton](/James_Wharton,_Baron_Wharton_of_Yarm), who adopted it as a [Private member's bill](/Private_member%27s_bill), subsequently known as the [European Union (Referendum) Bill 2013](/European_Union_(Referendum)_Bill_2013). &#91;19&#93; Its First Reading in the [House of Commons](/House_of_Commons_of_the_United_Kingdom) occurred on 19 June 2013. &#91;20&#93; Cameron, through a spokesperson, expressed his "great pleasure" and pledged the "full support of the Conservative Party" for the bill's passage. &#91;21&#93;

Regarding the bill's capacity to legally bind the [UK Government](/Government_of_the_United_Kingdom) of the [2015–20 Parliament](/List_of_MPs_elected_in_the_2015_United_Kingdom_general_election) (which, with a touch of cosmic irony, would only last two years due to the very referendum it enabled) to holding such a vote, a parliamentary research paper offered a dose of cautious realism: "The Bill simply provides for a referendum on continued EU membership by the end of December 2017 and does not otherwise specify the timing, other than requiring the Secretary of State to bring forward orders by the end of 2016. [...] If no party obtained a majority at the [next general election due in 2015], there might be some uncertainty about the passage of the orders in the next Parliament." &#91;22&#93; A rather polite way of saying "things could get messy."

Indeed, messy they became. The bill received its Second Reading on 5 July 2013, passing by a seemingly overwhelming 304 votes to none – largely because almost all [Labour](/Labour_Party_(UK)) and [Liberal Democrat](/Liberal_Democrats_(UK)) MPs chose to abstain, a strategic move that left the field clear. It cleared the Commons in November 2013, but its journey was halted in December 2013 when members of the [House of Lords](/House_of_Lords) voted to block it. &#91;23&#93;

Undaunted, Conservative [MP](/Member_of_parliament) [Bob Neill](/Bob_Neill) then introduced an Alternative Referendum Bill to the Commons. &#91;24&#93; &#91;25&#93; After a debate on 17 October 2014, it progressed to the [Public Bills Committee](/Public_bill_committee). However, a crucial procedural step was missed: the Commons failed to pass a money resolution, effectively preventing the bill from advancing further before the [dissolution of parliament](/Dissolution_of_parliament) on 27 March 2015. &#91;26&#93; &#91;27&#93;

The political landscape was also shifting, notably illustrated by the [European Parliament election in 2014](/2014_European_Parliament_election_in_the_United_Kingdom). For the first time in 108 years, a party other than the traditional [Conservatives](/Conservative_Party_(UK)) or [Labour](/Labour_Party_(UK)) topped a nationwide poll: the [UK Independence Party](/UK_Independence_Party) (UKIP) secured more votes and seats than any other party, leaving the Conservatives languishing in third place. &#91;28&#93; This was a clear signal of growing Eurosceptic sentiment.

Under [Ed Miliband](/Ed_Miliband)'s leadership between 2010 and 2015, the [Labour Party](/Labour_Party_(UK)) had generally ruled out an "in-out" referendum unless a further transfer of powers from the [UK](/United_Kingdom) to the [EU](/European_Union) was proposed. &#91;29&#93; The [Liberal Democrats](/Liberal_Democrats_(UK)), in their manifesto for the [2015 general election](/2015_United_Kingdom_general_election), similarly pledged a referendum only if changes to the [EU treaties](/Treaties_of_the_European_Union) were on the table. &#91;30&#93; Meanwhile, a diverse collection of parties, including the [UK Independence Party](/UK_Independence_Party) (UKIP), the [British National Party](/British_National_Party) (BNP), the [Green Party](/Green_Party_of_England_and_Wales), &#91;31&#93; the [Democratic Unionist Party](/Democratic_Unionist_Party) &#91;32&#93; and the [Respect Party](/Respect_Party) &#91;33&#93;, all vocally supported the fundamental principle of holding a referendum.

The dice were finally cast when the [Conservative Party](/Conservative_Party_(UK)) secured an outright majority of seats in the [House of Commons](/House_of_Commons_of_the_United_Kingdom) at the [2015 general election](/2015_United_Kingdom_general_election). [David Cameron](/David_Cameron) promptly reiterated his party's [manifesto](/Manifesto) commitment: an "in-out" referendum on [UK](/United_Kingdom) membership of the [EU](/European_Union) would indeed be held by the end of 2017, but only after "negotiating a new settlement for Britain in the EU." &#91;34&#93; The stage was set for the drama to unfold.

Renegotiation before the referendum

Main articles: [2015–2016 United Kingdom renegotiation of European Union membership](/2015%E2%80%932016_United_Kingdom_renegotiation_of_European_Union_membership) and [Law of the European Union](/Law_of_the_European_Union)

In early 2014, [David Cameron](/David_Cameron), with an air of determined optimism, began to articulate the precise changes he sought to achieve within the [EU](/European_Union) and, by extension, in the [UK](/United_Kingdom)'s often-strained relationship with it. &#91;35&#93; His shopping list of demands included: enhanced immigration controls, particularly targeting citizens from newer [EU member states](/EU_member_states); stricter immigration regulations for existing [EU citizens](/EU_citizen); novel powers allowing national parliaments, acting collectively, to veto proposed [EU laws](/Law_of_the_European_Union); the pursuit of new free-trade agreements coupled with a reduction in bureaucratic burdens for businesses; a diminution of the [European Court of Human Rights](/European_Court_of_Human_Rights)'s influence on British policing and legal systems; a general shift of power towards individual member states and away from the central [EU](/European_Union) apparatus; and, perhaps most symbolically, an abandonment of the [EU](/European_Union)'s guiding principle of "ever closer union." &#91;35&#93; His strategy was to secure these concessions through a series of negotiations with other [EU leaders](/European_Council_President) and then, assuming re-election, present this "new settlement" to the British public in a referendum. &#91;35&#93;

By November of that year, Cameron provided an update on these ongoing negotiations, offering further granular detail regarding his objectives. &#91;36&#93; The primary demands presented to the [EU](/European_Union) were multifaceted: concerning economic governance, he sought official recognition that laws pertaining to the [Eurozone](/Eurozone) would not automatically apply to non-Eurozone [EU members](/EU_member_states), and, crucially, that these non-Eurozone states would not be compelled to bail out struggling Eurozone economies. On the front of competitiveness, the aim was to expand the [single market](/Single_market) and establish a concrete target for reducing bureaucracy impacting businesses. Regarding sovereignty, the [UK](/United_Kingdom) desired a legally binding exemption from the commitment to "ever closer union," along with empowering national parliaments to collectively veto proposed [EU laws](/Law_of_the_European_Union). Finally, on the highly sensitive issue of immigration, Cameron pushed for a mechanism to prevent [EU citizens](/EU_citizen) arriving in the [UK](/United_Kingdom) for work from claiming social housing or in-work benefits until they had resided and worked there for four years. Furthermore, he sought to restrict their ability to send [child benefit](/Child_benefit) payments overseas. &#91;36&#93; &#91;37&#93;

The culmination of these renegotiations was unveiled in February 2016. &#91;38&#93; The resulting "renegotiated terms" were presented as additions to the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom)'s already extensive portfolio of [opt-outs in the European Union](/United_Kingdom_opt-outs_from_EU_legislation) and the unique [UK rebate](/UK_rebate). The actual significance of these modifications to the [EU–UK agreement](/United_Kingdom%E2%80%93European_Union_relations) was, as expected, a subject of intense debate and speculation. While few of the changes were universally considered "fundamental," some were indeed deemed important to a significant portion of the British populace. &#91;38&#93;

Specifically, some limits on in-work benefits for [EU immigrants](/Freedom_of_movement_for_workers_in_the_European_Union) were agreed upon. However, these would be applied on a sliding scale over four years and would only affect new immigrants. Even then, the implementation would require a country to first obtain permission from the [European Council](/European_Council). &#91;38&#93; The contentious issue of [child benefit](/Child_benefit) payments sent overseas was addressed by linking them to the cost of living in the recipient country, rather than outright banning them. &#91;39&#93; On the matter of sovereignty, the [UK](/United_Kingdom) received reassurances that it would not be compelled to participate in "ever closer union," though these assurances were largely "in line with existing [EU law](/Law_of_the_European_Union)." &#91;38&#93; Cameron's demand for national parliaments to veto proposed [EU laws](/Law_of_the_European_Union) was watered down to a mechanism allowing national parliaments to collectively object to proposals, at which point the [European Council](/European_Council) would reconsider before making its own final decision. &#91;38&#93; In terms of economic governance, anti-discrimination regulations for non-Eurozone members were to be strengthened, but these members would, critically, retain no power to veto legislation. &#91;40&#93; The agreement also touched upon proposals to "exclude from the scope of free movement rights, third country nationals who had no prior lawful residence in a Member State before marrying a Union citizen" &#91;41&#93; and to facilitate the deportation of [EU nationals](/EU_citizen) for reasons of public policy or security. &#91;42&#93; The legal enforceability of these various components was, predictably, complex, as no part of the agreement itself fundamentally altered [EU law](/Law_of_the_European_Union), though some elements might be enforceable under international law. &#91;43&#93;

Intriguingly, the [EU](/European_Union) had reportedly extended an offer to [David Cameron](/David_Cameron): a so-called "emergency brake" that would have permitted the [UK](/United_Kingdom) to suspend social benefits for new immigrants for their initial four years in the country, a measure that could have been applied for a period of seven years. &#91;44&#93; This offer, a potential lifeline for Cameron's domestic agenda, remained on the table right up until the Brexit referendum. However, it expired, unactivated, when the vote determined the [UK](/United_Kingdom) would leave the [EU](/European_Union). Cameron later claimed, as reported by the [Financial Times](/Financial_Times), that "he could have avoided Brexit had European leaders let him control migration." &#91;45&#93; &#91;46&#93; A convenient narrative, perhaps, but one famously contradicted by [Angela Merkel](/Angela_Merkel), who, speaking in the German Parliament, stated unequivocally that the offer had not been made by the [EU](/European_Union). Merkel's firm stance was: "If you wish to have free access to the single market then you have to accept the fundamental European rights as well as obligations that come from it. This is as true for Great Britain as for anybody else." &#91;47&#93; A stark reminder that the [EU](/European_Union) plays by its own rules, regardless of domestic political pressures.

Legislation

See also: [European Union Referendum Act 2015](/European_Union_Referendum_Act_2015)

The much-anticipated referendum, the subject of considerable political maneuvering, was formally included in the [Queen's Speech](/State_Opening_of_Parliament) on 27 May 2015. &#91;48&#93; At the time, whispers suggested that [David Cameron](/David_Cameron) was contemplating an earlier referendum date, perhaps in October 2016. &#91;49&#93; However, the actual legislative instrument, the [European Union Referendum Act 2015](/European_Union_Referendum_Act_2015), which provided the legal authority for the vote, was brought before the [House of Commons](/House_of_Commons_of_the_United_Kingdom) with remarkable speed, just one day later, a mere three weeks after the general election. &#91;50&#93;

During the bill's second reading on 9 June, Members of the [House of Commons](/House_of_Commons_of_the_United_Kingdom) endorsed the principle of holding a referendum by a decisive vote of 544 to 53, with only the [Scottish National Party](/Scottish_National_Party) casting dissenting votes. &#91;51&#93; In a notable shift from the [Labour Party](/Labour_Party_(UK))'s stance prior to the [2015 general election](/2015_United_Kingdom_general_election) under [Ed Miliband](/Ed_Miliband), acting Labour leader [Harriet Harman](/Harriet_Harman) committed her party to supporting the plans for an [EU referendum](/European_Union) by 2017. This position was subsequently maintained by the newly elected leader, [Jeremy Corbyn](/Jeremy_Corbyn). &#91;52&#93;

To transform the proposed referendum into a legal reality, the [European Union Referendum Act](/European_Union_Referendum_Act_2015) &#91;53&#93; was duly passed by the [Parliament of the United Kingdom](/Parliament_of_the_United_Kingdom). Its legislative reach was deliberately extended to include [Gibraltar](/Gibraltar), &#91;54&#93; &#91;55&#93; and it received royal assent on 17 December 2015. This Act was then further confirmed, enacted, and implemented within [Gibraltar](/Gibraltar) itself by the [European Union (Referendum) Act 2016 (Gibraltar)](/European_Union_(Referendum)_Act_2016_(Gibraltar)), &#91;56&#93; which successfully passed through the [Gibraltar Parliament](/Gibraltar_Parliament) and became law upon receiving the assent of the [Governor of Gibraltar](/Governor_of_Gibraltar) on 28 January 2016. A truly multinational legislative effort for a very British problem.

The [European Union Referendum Act](/European_Union_Referendum_Act_2015) was clear in its primary objective: it mandated that a referendum be held on the question of the [UK](/United_Kingdom)'s continued membership of the [European Union](/European_Union) before the close of 2017. What it conspicuously *did not* contain, however, was any explicit requirement for the [UK Government](/Government_of_the_United_Kingdom) to actually implement the results. Instead, its design was merely to "gauge the electorate's opinion" on [EU](/European_Union) membership. This distinction is crucial; it placed the referendum in a category similar to the devolution referendums held in Scotland, Wales, and Northern Ireland in 1997 and 1998, where public sentiment was ascertained *before* any subsequent legislation was introduced.

Unlike, for instance, the [Republic of Ireland](/Republic_of_Ireland), where specific constitutional provisions dictate when a binding referendum must be held, the [UK](/United_Kingdom) lacks such explicit constitutional mandates for implementing referendum results. &#91;57&#93; To illustrate the contrast, the legislation for the [Alternative Vote referendum](/2011_United_Kingdom_Alternative_Vote_referendum) in May 2011 *would* have automatically implemented the new voting system without further parliamentary action, provided certain boundary changes were also enacted. In that instance, a substantial majority rejected the proposed change. The 1975 [EC membership referendum](/1975_United_Kingdom_European_Communities_membership_referendum), for its part, was conducted only after the renegotiated terms of the [UK](/United_Kingdom)'s [EC](/European_Communities) membership had been agreed upon by all [EC Member States](/Member_state_of_the_European_Union), with these terms explicitly laid out in a command paper and approved by both Houses of Parliament. &#91;57&#93; Following the 2016 vote, the High Court unequivocally confirmed that the result was not legally binding, a conclusion rooted in the constitutional bedrock of [parliamentary sovereignty](/Parliamentary_sovereignty_in_the_United_Kingdom) and representative democracy. The legislation authorizing the referendum simply did not contain the clear, unambiguous language that would have made it so. &#91;58&#93;

Referendum question

Sample referendum ballot paper

The [Electoral Commission](/Electoral_Commission_(United_Kingdom)), in its meticulous research, confidently asserted that its recommended question was both "clear and straightforward for voters" and "the most neutral wording from the range of options... considered and tested." This claim was backed by responses gathered during its consultation process, which involved a diverse array of consultees. &#91;59&#93; The government, seemingly in agreement, accepted the proposed question in September 2015, just prior to the bill's third reading. &#91;60&#93;

The precise question that voters encountered on their ballot papers under the provisions of the [European Union Referendum Act 2015](/European_Union_Referendum_Act_2015) was as follows:

`Should the United Kingdom remain a member of the European Union or leave the European Union?`

Accompanying this, the responses to be marked with a single 'X' were:

`•`
`Remain a member of the European Union`
`•`
`Leave the European Union`

For the benefit of Welsh speakers, the question was also provided in the [Welsh language](/Welsh_language):

`A ddylai'r Deyrnas Unedig aros yn aelod o'r Undeb Ewropeaidd neu adael yr Undeb Ewropeaidd?`

With the corresponding responses (also to be marked with a single 'X'):

`•`
`Aros yn aelod o'r Undeb Ewropeaidd`
`•`
`Gadael yr Undeb Ewropeaidd`

Administration

Date

Before the official announcement, political pundits and informed observers widely speculated that a June date for the referendum was a distinct and serious possibility. The First Ministers of Northern Ireland, Scotland, and Wales, in a rare display of cross-devolved unity, co-signed a letter to [David Cameron](/David_Cameron) on 3 February 2016. Their plea? To avoid holding the referendum in June, as devolved elections were already slated for the preceding month, 5 May. These elections had, themselves, already been delayed by a year to prevent a clash with the [2015 general election](/2015_United_Kingdom_general_election), a consequence of Westminster's implementation of the [Fixed-term Parliament Act](/Fixed-term_Parliaments_Act_2011). Cameron, however, politely but firmly declined this request, asserting that the public was perfectly capable of making informed decisions in multiple elections, provided they were spaced at least six weeks apart. &#91;61&#93; &#91;62&#93; A testament to human multitasking, or perhaps just political expediency.

On 20 February 2016, [David Cameron](/David_Cameron) formally declared that the [UK Government](/Government_of_the_United_Kingdom) would officially recommend that the British populace vote to remain a member of a "reformed" [European Union](/European_Union). He simultaneously announced that the referendum itself would take place on 23 June, thereby marking the official launch of the campaign. He also stated that Parliament would enact the necessary secondary legislation on 22 February, directly related to the [European Union Referendum Act 2015](/European_Union_Referendum_Act_2015). With this official launch, ministers of the [UK Government](/Government_of_the_United_Kingdom) were, in a rare departure from the usual strictures of [Cabinet collective responsibility](/Cabinet_collective_responsibility), granted the freedom to publicly campaign on either side of the argument. &#91;63&#93; A truly unique moment in British political history, allowing for a spectacular internal party civil war to play out in public.

Eligibility to vote

The legislation meticulously defined the right to vote in the referendum within the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom). It was restricted to residents of the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom) who were either also [Commonwealth citizens](/Commonwealth_of_Nations) under Section 37 of the [British Nationality Act 1981](/British_Nationality_Act_1981) (a category encompassing [British citizens](/British_Nationality_Act_1981) and other [British nationals](/British_nationality)), or those who also held [citizenship of the Republic of Ireland](/Irish_nationality_law), or both. Notably, members of the [House of Lords](/House_of_Lords), typically disenfranchised in general elections, were, for this historic vote, granted the right to cast their ballots. The total electorate, encompassing 46,500,001 individuals, represented a significant 70.8% of the combined population of the [UK](/Demographics_of_the_United_Kingdom) and [Gibraltar](/Demographics_of_Gibraltar) (totaling 65,678,000). &#91;64&#93; Curiously, with the sole exception of the residents of [Gibraltar](/Gibraltar), other British Overseas Territories Citizens residing in the various British Overseas Territories were conspicuously excluded from participating in the referendum. &#91;65&#93; &#91;66&#93;

Residents of the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom) who held citizenship of other [EU countries](/EU_member_states) were generally not permitted to vote, unless they also happened to be citizens of the [Republic of Ireland](/Republic_of_Ireland), [Malta](/Malta), or the Republic of [Cyprus](/Cyprus). &#91;67&#93;

The [Representation of the People Acts 1983](/Representation_of_the_People_Act_1983) (1983 c. 2) and [1985](/Representation_of_the_People_Act_1985) (1985 c. 50), as amended, also extended voting rights to certain British citizens (though not other British nationals) who had previously resided in the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom) but had since lived abroad for a period not exceeding 15 years. &#91;68&#93;

On the day of the referendum, polling stations were open from 07:00 to 22:00 [BST](/British_Summer_Time) ([WEST](/Western_European_Summer_Time)) (or 07:00 to 22:00 [CEST](/Central_European_Summer_Time) in [Gibraltar](/Gibraltar)). Approximately 41,000 polling stations were established, staffed by a small army of over 100,000 [poll workers](/Poll_workers). Each polling station was meticulously capped at a maximum of 2,500 registered voters. &#91;citation needed&#93; In accordance with the [Representation of the People Act 2000](/Representation_of_the_People_Act_2000), postal ballots were also permitted and were dispatched to eligible voters roughly three weeks before the actual vote, specifically on 2 June 2016.

The minimum voting age for the referendum was set at 18 years, aligning with the existing [Representation of the People Act](/Representation_of_the_People_Act_1983), as amended. An attempt by the [House of Lords](/House_of_Lords) to lower this minimum age to 16 years was ultimately rejected. &#91;69&#93;

The initial deadline for voter registration was set for midnight on 7 June 2016. However, a surge of unusually high web traffic caused technical problems with the official registration website on that day, necessitating a 48-hour extension. This decision drew criticism from some 'Leave' campaigners, including Conservative [MP](/Member_of_parliament) [Sir Gerald Howarth](/Sir_Gerald_Howarth), who alleged it unfairly benefited the 'Remain' campaign, given that many late registrants were young people, generally perceived to be more inclined to vote 'Remain'. &#91;70&#93; Provisional figures from the [Electoral Commission](/Electoral_Commission_(United_Kingdom)) indicated that almost 46.5 million individuals were eligible to cast their vote. &#91;71&#93;

Registration problems

[Nottingham City Council](/Nottingham_City_Council) found itself in an awkward position when it informed a [Vote Leave](/Vote_Leave) supporter via email that the council lacked the means to verify the nationality declared by individuals on their voter registration forms. Consequently, they were compelled to operate on the assumption that the information submitted was, in fact, accurate. &#91;72&#93; A rather trusting system, one might observe.

Compounding these issues, 3,462 [EU nationals](/EU_citizen) were erroneously sent postal voting cards. This glitch was attributed to an IT problem experienced by Xpress, a software supplier specializing in electoral systems for numerous councils. Initially, Xpress struggled to confirm the exact number of individuals affected. The problem was eventually rectified through the deployment of a software patch, which, somewhat belatedly, rendered the incorrectly registered electors ineligible to vote on 23 June. &#91;72&#93; A minor bureaucratic hiccup, perhaps, but one that certainly didn't soothe the already frayed nerves of the electorate.

Crown Dependencies

Residents of the [Crown Dependencies](/Crown_Dependencies)—territories not formally part of the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom), specifically the [Isle of Man](/Isle_of_Man) and the Bailiwicks of [Jersey](/Jersey) and [Guernsey](/Guernsey)—found themselves excluded from the referendum. This exclusion applied even if they held British citizenship, unless they had previously resided in the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom) itself (meaning England and Wales, Scotland, and Northern Ireland). &#91;73&#93;

This disenfranchisement did not go unnoticed. Some residents of the [Isle of Man](/Isle_of_Man) voiced their objections, arguing that as full British citizens under the [British Nationality Act 1981](/British_Nationality_Act_1981) and inhabitants of the [British Islands](/British_Islands), they too should have been afforded the opportunity to vote. Their argument rested on the undeniable fact that the Isle and the Bailiwicks, despite not being considered part of the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom) for the purposes of [European Union](/European_Union) (and [European Economic Area](/European_Economic_Area) (EEA)) membership, would nonetheless be significantly impacted by the referendum's outcome. &#91;73&#93; A logical point, perhaps, but logic often finds itself at the bottom of the pile in matters of national identity.

Campaign

Main article: [Campaigning in the 2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum](/Campaigning_in_the_2016_United_Kingdom_European_Union_membership_referendum)

See also: [Allegations of unlawful campaigning in the 2016 EU referendum](/Allegations_of_unlawful_campaigning_in_the_2016_EU_referendum)
[Britain Stronger in Europe](/Britain_Stronger_in_Europe) campaigners, London, June 2016 Referendum posters for both the Leave and Remain campaigns in [Pimlico](/Pimlico), London
Remain campaign "I'm in" sticker

The official campaign machinery began its grind in October 2015 with the formation of [Britain Stronger in Europe](/Britain_Stronger_in_Europe), a cross-party coalition dedicated to advocating for the [UK](/United_Kingdom)'s continued membership of the [EU](/European_Union). &#91;74&#93; On the opposing side, the 'Leave' camp was a rather less cohesive affair, with two primary rival groups vying for the coveted "official" designation: [Leave.EU](/Leave.EU), which enjoyed the backing of most of [UKIP](/UKIP) (including its most prominent figure, [Nigel Farage](/Nigel_Farage)), and [Vote Leave](/Vote_Leave), which was the favoured choice of influential [Conservative Party Eurosceptics](/Euroscepticism_in_the_United_Kingdom). The internal squabbling between these two factions became so pronounced that in January 2016, [Nigel Farage](/Nigel_Farage) and the [Leave.EU](/Leave.EU) campaign eventually merged into the larger, if still somewhat fractious, [Grassroots Out](/Grassroots_Out) movement. &#91;75&#93; &#91;76&#93;

The [Electoral Commission](/Electoral_Commission_(United_Kingdom)) finally intervened in April, officially designating [Britain Stronger in Europe](/Britain_Stronger_in_Europe) as the official 'Remain' campaign and [Vote Leave](/Vote_Leave) as the official 'Leave' campaign. &#91;77&#93; This designation came with tangible benefits, including the right to spend up to a rather generous £7,000,000, a free mailshot to every household, dedicated television broadcasts, and a not-insignificant £600,000 in public funds. The [UK Government](/Government_of_the_United_Kingdom)'s official position, as declared by [David Cameron](/David_Cameron), was to support the 'Remain' campaign. However, in a rare and rather dramatic exception to the principle of [cabinet collective responsibility](/Cabinet_collective_responsibility), Cameron announced that Conservative Ministers and [MPs](/Member_of_parliament) were free to campaign for either side, according to their individual conscience. &#91;78&#93; &#91;79&#93; This decision came after considerable internal pressure for a "free vote" for ministers, effectively sanctioning a civil war within the ruling party. A Government-backed campaign, complete with its own leaflet, was launched in April. &#91;80&#93; Tragically, on 16 June, all official national campaigning was suspended until 19 June following the brutal [murder of Jo Cox](/Murder_of_Jo_Cox), a pro-EU Labour [MP](/Member_of_parliament). &#91;81&#93;

After internal polls revealed that a staggering 85% of the [UK](/United_Kingdom) population desired more information from the government regarding the referendum, [a leaflet](/Pro-EU_leaflet) was dispatched to every household across the nation. &#91;82&#93; This publication meticulously outlined the government's rationale for believing that continued [EU](/European_Union) membership was the optimal path for the [UK](/United_Kingdom). Unsurprisingly, this taxpayer-funded initiative, which cost a cool £9.3 million, drew sharp criticism from 'Leave' campaigners, who decried it as an unfair advantage for the 'Remain' side, not to mention a wasteful use of public funds and riddled with inaccuracies. &#91;83&#93; During the campaign, [Nigel Farage](/Nigel_Farage) provocatively suggested that a narrow 'Remain' victory (e.g., closer than 52–48%) would inevitably lead to public demand for a second referendum, precisely because the government leaflet had, in his view, allowed the 'Remain' side to outspend their opponents. &#91;84&#93;

In the week commencing 16 May, the [Electoral Commission](/Electoral_Commission_(United_Kingdom)), in its capacity as impartial arbiter, sent a comprehensive voting guide to every household in the [UK](/United_Kingdom) and [Gibraltar](/Gibraltar). This eight-page booklet, designed to raise awareness, included practical details on how to vote, a sample of the actual ballot paper, and, critically, a full page allocated to both [Britain Stronger in Europe](/Britain_Stronger_in_Europe) and [Vote Leave](/Vote_Leave) to present their respective cases. &#91;85&#93; &#91;86&#93;

The [Vote Leave](/Vote_Leave) campaign, in its core argument, posited that exiting the [EU](/European_Union) would safeguard national [sovereignty](/Sovereignty), enable the implementation of stricter immigration controls, and free the [UK](/United_Kingdom) to forge independent trade deals across the globe. Furthermore, they highlighted the cessation of weekly membership payments to the [EU](/European_Union). &#91;87&#93; &#91;note 1&#93; Conversely, the [Britain Stronger in Europe](/Britain_Stronger_in_Europe) campaign argued that a departure from the [European Union](/European_Union) would inflict significant damage upon the [UK economy](/Economic_effects_of_Brexit) and fundamentally undermine the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom)'s standing and influence on the world stage, which they contended was inextricably linked to its membership. &#91;90&#93;

Responses to the referendum campaign

Party policies

In the frenetic period leading up to the referendum, a significant majority of the 650 [MPs](/Member_of_parliament) elected to the [2015-17 UK Parliament](/List_of_MPs_elected_in_the_2015_United_Kingdom_general_election) publicly declared their intention to vote in favour of remaining in the [European Union](/European_Union). Specifically, 479 [MPs](/Member_of_parliament) aligned with 'Remain,' a stark contrast to the 158 who publicly committed to 'Leave.'
